{"title":"Welcome","markdown":{"headingText":"Welcome","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n## Why this course exists\n\nMost R textbooks teach syntax first and hope the motivation follows. This course does the opposite. Every page opens with a problem you might actually be handed as a public health intern, a research assistant, an epidemiology student, or a data analyst on a health department team — and you learn exactly the R you need, at the moment you need it, to solve it.\n\nYou will not find a chapter that starts with \"Today we will learn the `filter()` function.\" Instead you will find a supervisor asking you to find every participant over 65 with hypertension, and `filter()` will show up as the tool that gets you out of that jam.\n\n## Who this is for\n\nThis course assumes **zero prior programming experience**. If you have never written a line of code in your life but you can think through a problem logically, you are the target reader. It is built for students and professionals in:\n\nPublic health, epidemiology, biostatistics, clinical research, health data analysis, survey research, and population health.\n\nBy the final capstone level, the material assumes you have worked through everything before it — the course is cumulative, not a reference manual to jump around in on your first pass.\n\n## How each lesson works\n\nEvery lesson in this book follows the same rhythm, because the rhythm itself is what builds problem-solving skill:\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**1. Real-World Problem** — a short, realistic scenario from health research.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**2. Your Mission** — the concrete task you need to accomplish.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-think}\n**3. Think Before Coding** — a few questions to reason through before touching the keyboard.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-concept}\n**4. The R Concept** — the one new idea you need, explained plainly: what it does, its syntax, its arguments, and what usually goes wrong.\n:::\n\n**5. Demonstration** — runnable R code showing the concept in isolation.\n\n**6. Explore** — small modifications you make to that code to test your understanding.\n\n**7. Solve the Problem** — you return to the opening scenario and solve it completely.\n\n**8. Interpret the Result** — the output translated into a plain-language sentence a supervisor or reader would understand.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mistake}\n**9. Common Mistakes** — errors beginners reliably make with this concept, and why they happen.\n:::\n\n**10. Practice Problem** — a new, similar problem for you to solve with support.\n\n**11. Challenge Problem** — a harder variant you solve with less scaffolding.\n\n**12. Key Takeaways** — two to four sentences worth remembering.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-check}\n**13. Knowledge Check** — multiple-choice, true/false, predict-the-output, find-the-error, and write-the-code questions, with answers hidden behind a toggle so you can self-test honestly.\n:::\n\n## The dataset you'll live in\n\nRather than switching example datasets every page, most of this course reuses a single running dataset: a simulated **community health survey of 100 participants**, with age, sex, county, systolic and diastolic blood pressure, BMI, and smoking status — including realistic missing values. You'll meet it for the first time in Level 1 and return to it constantly, so that learning R and learning to think about a real dataset happen together. The file lives at `data/participants.csv`.\n\nBy Level 15 you'll be running full analyses — and eventually independent capstone projects — on data structured just like it.\n\n## Course map\n\n| Level | Focus |\n|---|---|\n| 1 | Getting started: R, RStudio, objects, basic types |\n| 2 | Data structures: vectors, data frames, lists, tibbles |\n| 3 | Importing and exporting real data files |\n| 4 | Cleaning messy data in base R |\n| 5 | The tidyverse: `dplyr`, pipes, and friends |\n| 6 | Reshaping and joining datasets |\n| 7 | Descriptive statistics |\n| 8 | Data visualization with `ggplot2` |\n| 9 | Writing functions and `purrr` |\n| 10 | Loops and automation |\n| 11 | Statistical analysis: t-tests through survival models |\n| 12 | Advanced analysis: confounding, mixed models, surveys |\n| 13 | Advanced R programming: OOP, debugging, packages |\n| 14 | Reproducible research with Quarto |\n| 15 | Capstone research projects, start to finish |\n\n## What you'll be able to do\n\nBy the end, starting from zero, you will be able to navigate R and RStudio, write and debug your own R code, understand R's core data structures, import and clean real-world health data, manipulate data fluently with the tidyverse, build publication-quality figures, write your own functions and automate repetitive analysis, run and interpret the statistical methods most common in health research, work with longitudinal, survey, and time-to-event data, and produce a fully reproducible research report from raw data to final results — in Quarto, from scratch.\n\nLet's start with the question every beginner has: what is R, actually, and why are we bothering?\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-